<DOC><DOCNO> AP881212-0158 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-12-88 1930EST</FILEID><FIRST>r w AM-BRF--MedalistRetiring     12-12 0160</FIRST><SECOND>AM-BRF--Medalist Retiring,150</SECOND><HEAD>First Vietnam-Era Medal of Honor Winner To Retire</HEAD><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Army Col. Roger H.C. Donlon, the firstserviceman to win a Medal of Honor for valor during the Vietnam War,will retire later this week after 32 years of military service, thePentagon announced Monday.   Donlon was awarded the Medal of Honor by President Johnson duringa White House ceremony on Dec. 5, 1964, in recognition of hisbravery in repulsing a Viet Cong attack at Nam Dong on July 6, 1964.   Donlon, who is the alternate-president of the Army's PhysicalEvaluation Board at the Presidio of San Francisco, will retireduring ceremonies scheduled Wednesday morning at Fort Leavenworth,Kan., the Pentagon said.   ``He and his wife, Norma, will reside in Leavenworth,'' thePentagon added.   Besides the Medal of Honor, Donlon also has won the Bronze Star,the Meritorious Service Medal with two Oak Leaf Clusters, the JointService Commendation Medal and a Purple Heart.</TEXT></DOC>